caption_original: Environment and Climate Change Canada is pleased to announce the 500th Ecological Gift in Ontario. Sandra Nelles generously donated a conservation easement over 38 hectares of her rural residential property to the Oak Ridges Moraine Land Trust that was certified through the Ecological Gifts Program. The conservation easement was specifically designed for her property and included protection zones to preserve forested areas that contain Butternut—a species of tree endangered in Canada—and zones for continued farming. Ms. Nelles retains ownership of the property, while restricting future development and protecting the ecological features of the land. http://ow.ly/Ej4d303GrZa http://ow.ly/H6se303Gs3l

caption_original:
Outdoor enthusiasts have long been drawn to the Montagnes Vertes region of southern Quebec. Its hiking trails and ski slopes offer unmatched views of the old-growth forest wilderness. The area is also home to wide-ranging mammals, including moose, bobcats, black bears and fishers, as well as a number of species at risk such as the Bicknell’s Thrush and Canada Warbler.
Environment and Climate Change Canada is working with the Nature Conservancy of Canada and local donors to greatly expand the Montagnes Vertes nature reserve around Mont Sutton to protect important wildlife habitat while continuing public access to the area’s natural beauty. http://ow.ly/GIfM303GsYE

Join us Friday, August 19th, at 12:00 p.m. PDT (3pm EDT) for a Facebook Live event hosted by Dr. Joyce Boye, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations’ Special Ambassador for the International Year of Pulses 2016! An internationally acclaimed scientist, Dr. Boye is the Director of Research, Development and Technology, at Agriculture Canada’s Agassiz and Summerland Research and Development Centres. Dr. Boye will be delivering a 30 minute presentation touching on the importance of the International Year of Pulses and her role as ambassador, as well as the benefits of pulses, and the many products that can be derived from this highly diversifiable crop.

Have your questions ready! As Dr. Boye will also be answering questions received in the comments during the event.

Don’t you hate shopping for an item advertised as “on sale” to find it’s already sold out? 

If the bargain you seek is out of stock, ask for a rain check. This will allow you to get the deal once the item has been re-stocked.

If a rain check is not offered and the seller cannot prove that the item was reasonably stocked or that it sold out due to reasons they were not able to control, it could be considered bait and switch selling—which is illegal.

Learn more: http://ow.ly/uats3034uYN

Did you know that the Cap Tourmente and Lac Saint Francois National Wildlife Areas in Quebec are designated as wetlands of international importance under the RAMSAR Convention? 
The Cap Tourmente wildlife area was the first site to receive this prestigious designation in North America in 1981. The benefits of wetlands are numerous: they filter our water and limit floods and erosion. They also provide feeding, breeding and nursery habitat for many species. It’s one of the most productive natural habitats on the planet. Let’s protect them!
http://ow.ly/1DMo3034yov

When you’re shopping, be cautious of marketing strategies designed to make you buy more than you need.

You may run into offers such as “BOGO—buy one item and get a second half off!” 

This may seem like a good deal, but in order to take advantage of it, you need to spend more than you originally planned. Plus, in the end you’re only getting half a deal when you have to buy twice as many shoes. 

More wise spending habits: http://ow.ly/n14V3034tsY

caption_original:
Introducing Poseidon, the recently named Floating Foundation Installer (FFI) operating on the new Champlain Bridge worksite.

Montreal youth attending the “Futurs Génies” day camp will have a great story to tell about their holidays when they head back to class! After all it’s not every day you get to name and build a replica of a massive construction machine.

And the winning name was Poseidon, which fittingly captures the machine’s impressive strength and important mission – placing large pieces of the new Champlain Bridge weighing up to 1,000 tonnes on the floor of the St. Lawrence.

Campers from the science and engineering camp offered through the École de Technologie supérieure, participated in the competition run by Signature on the Saint Lawrence (SSL), the private partner responsible for the New Champlain Bridge Corridor Project and local MP Mark Miller joined SSL to announce the winners.

caption_original: Wearing chemical resistant gloves and footwear can significantly reduce your exposure while handling pesticides. This special clothing or equipment (often called "PPE" for Personal Protective Equipment) is worn to minimize pesticide exposure and protect your health. This could include: chemical resistant unlined gloves and footwear, long-sleeved shirt and long pants, socks, or a respirator. Learn more about PPE from the Health Canada website: http://ow.ly/VxEc303xEWG
